                  snippet:
                    "For four quarters in a row, customer traffic across the company&#x27;s stores and website has fallen. Target&#x27;s net income for the three-month period that ended Jan. 31 fell to $1.05 billion, or $2.30 per share, compared with $1.10 billion, or $2.41 per share, a year earlier. Excluding one-time items, including legal settlement gains and business transformation costs, Target&#x27;s adjusted earnings per share were $2.44.\nTarget revenue and store traffic fell during its holiday quarter as the company tries to end a sales slump. The report is the first for the retailer since CEO Michael Fiddelke took over last month.\nFor four quarters in a row, customer traffic across the company's stores and website has fallen. Target's net income for the three-month period that ended Jan. 31 fell to $1.05 billion, or $2.30 per share, compared with $1.10 billion, or $2.41 per share, a year earlier. Excluding one-time items, including legal settlement gains and business transformation costs, Target's adjusted earnings per share were $2.44.\nAlong with offering products like groceries, clothing, and home goods, Target is trying to sell more advertisements and membership subscriptions to customers. The company's nonmerchandise sales jumped more than 25% in the fourth quarter, driven by membership revenue more than doubling from a year ago, double-digit percentage gains in its ads business, Roundel, and over 30% growth in its third-party marketplace.\nHere's what the company reported for the fiscal fourth quarter compared with Wall Street's estimates, according to a survey of analysts by LSEG:",
