                    "Q4 2025 Earnings Preview: Can Corporate Profits Sustain S&P 500 Record Highs?",
                  snippet:
                    'Revenues are expected to have grown 7.7% YoY, the 21st consecutive quarter of growth, and the second-strongest figure in three years. Eight of the 11 S&amp;P sectors are anticipated to post YoY gains, with Information Technology (25.9%), Materials ...\nEarnings season gets underway this week, with reports from major banks providing the first look at corporate performance \u00b7 The technology sector is expected to be the standout performer with over 25% projected earnings growth, driven by the ongoing "AI arms race" Sectors that rely on lower-end consumer spending are expected to be squeezed again by "value-conscious\u201d shoppers, making the consumer discretionary sector a laggard this season \u00b7 The Q4 2025 earnings season for US corporations begins this week when big banks kick things off, starting with JPMorgan Chase on Tuesday (Jan 13).\nNext week we\u2019ll not only hear from US corporations as they wrap up 2025 with their Q4 results, but get their much-anticipated outlooks for 2026. The current consensus for Q4 S&P 500 EPS growth stands at 8.3% according to FactSet. This would be the 10th consecutive quarter of growth for the index.\nRevenues are expected to have grown 7.7% YoY, the 21st consecutive quarter of growth, and the second-strongest figure in three years. Eight of the 11 S&P sectors are anticipated to post YoY gains, with Information Technology (25.9%), Materials (9.0%) and Financials (6.4%) leading the pack. Only Industrials (-0.5%), Energy (-1.7%) and Consumer Discretionary (-3.5%) are expected to post negative growth.1 \u00b7 Overall, 2025 EPS growth is expected to come in at 12.4%. For 2026 that figure is anticipated to improve to 14.9%.2\nNvidia\u2019s Blowout and Retail\u2019s Resilience in the Last Big Week for Q4 Earnings \u00b7 Split Decisions: What Stock Splits Reveal About Today\u2019s Economy and Market \u00b7 Economic Data Alphabet Soup on the Menu: FOMC Minutes, GDP, PCE, PMIs, UMich \u00b7 Earnings Hold the Line as Retailers get Ready to Report Amid Major Sector Rotation and Tech Fallout',
