            data_html:
              "# Summary of Q4 2025 Search Findings\n\n## Key Corporate Earnings Reports\n\n**Technology Sector:**\n- **SAP**: Strong cloud quarter with 30% Total Cloud Backlog growth to \u20ac77 billion; AI integration drove two-thirds of Q4 cloud orders\n- **Microsoft**: Revenue in More Personal Computing reached $13.5 billion (up 9%); returned $9.4 billion to shareholders\n- **IBM**: Delivered strong double-digit Software and Infrastructure revenue growth; generative AI book of business exceeded $12.5 billion\n- **Tesla**: Q4 and full-year 2025 results available (specific figures not detailed in search)\n\n**Retail Sector:**\n- **Target**: Net income fell to $1.05 billion ($2.30/share) from $1.10 billion year-over-year; customer traffic declined for fourth consecutive quarter, though non-merchandise sales jumped 25%\n- **Dollar Tree**: Q4 comparable store sales grew 5.0%; full-year net sales increased 10%\n\n**Specialized Companies:**\n- **Ondas Inc.**: Q4 revenue of $30.1 million; full-year 2025 revenue of $50.7 million (605% YoY growth); projects 2026 revenue of at least $375 million (7-fold increase)\n- **Nordic Semiconductor**: Consumer revenue reached $100 million in Q4 2025 (4% increase from Q4 2024)\n- **ABB**: Record quarterly orders of $10.3 billion; annual free cash flow reached record $4.6 billion\n\n## Banking &amp; Financial Services\n\n**FDIC Banking Industry (Q4 2025):**\n- Aggregate net income: $77.7 billion (down 2% from Q3)\n- Return on Assets (ROA): 1.24%\n- Full-year 2025 net income: $295.6 billion (up 10.2% from 2024)\n- Deposit Insurance Fund balance: $153.9 billion\n- Community banks showed strong performance with full-year ROA of 1.32%\n\n## Market Trends &amp; Forecasts\n\n**S&amp;P 500 Earnings Preview:**\n- Expected EPS growth: 8.3% (10th consecutive quarter of growth)\n- Revenue growth projected: 7.7% YoY (21st consecutive quarter)\n- Technology sector leading with 25.9% projected growth\n- Full-year 2025 EPS growth: 12.4%; 2026 forecast: 14.9%\n\n**Private Markets:**\n- U.S. direct lending volumes reached $380 billion for full-year 2025\n- New-money issuance: $248 billion\n- Real estate recovery flattened in second half of 2025\n\n**Small Business Index:**\n- 70% of small businesses report good health\n- 44% expect to increase investment in next year\n- 65% anticipate revenue increases\n- Competition and compliance burdens decreased from Q3\n\n## Overall Assessment\n\nQ4 2025 showed strong performance across technology sectors driven by AI adoption, while retail faced consumer spending challenges. The banking industry demonstrated robust earnings and capital strength. Corporate America generally exceeded expectations with broad-based growth, though some sectors showed signs of moderation heading into 2026.",
